1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:23,000
Today, excuse me, today is Tuesday, July 26, 2011. My name is Joe Manier of the Southern Oil History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:32,000
I'm in Detroit, Michigan with our project, the RFR John Bishop, to do an oil history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

4
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:41,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

5
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:44,000
And we're delighted today to be with Dr. William J. Anderson.

6
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Thank you for the welcome and for taking time from your schedule to the panelists.

7
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:57,000
And thank you for the opportunity of sharing my story, my experiences, if you would, in the Civil Rights Movement. I was privileged to be a part of it.

8
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Well, we're looking forward to the conversation. Absolutely. You were as a child and young man. You were very ambitious and an active young person. You graduated high school, I think, at age 15.

9
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Yes.

10
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:20,000
And I know that you came up in America, Georgia. And I wonder if you might just sort of get us started here.

11
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:25,000
They talked a little bit about the world of America's Georgia when you were gone now.

12
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:33,000
I very often compare the conditions under which I grew up in that amount of the King, Jr.

13
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Because we were barely 170 miles apart. We both experienced the same conditions.

14
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:48,000
That is, America's was a small farming community with perhaps 5,000, 6,000 people.

15
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:58,000
And the premier industries, of course, were farming peanuts, cotton, and even some pecans.

16
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:13,000
And my parents were somewhat educated as compared to others in that my father finished high school. And he started college, more house college, the most prestigious college for black men in the United States probably in the world.

17
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:18,000
But we don't know whether or not he ever graduated. But that was not important.

18
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:34,000
The important thing was he went to college, which was probably a single accomplishment within itself, because very, very few blacks, especially males, had the opportunity to go to college.

19
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:44,000
My mother, who was a high school graduate, and she was teaching school as a high school graduate because she happened to be one of the most educated people in town.

20
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:53,000
She went back to college after my sister, who was the youngest three children that she had, the youngest started school. Then she went back to college.

21
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:04,000
And she would go to college in the summer, or in a state by the way, that became historic. But she would go to school in the summer. And she would teach school during the school season.

22
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:18,000
It took her 20 years, but in that 20 years she got her BS degree, a major, major accomplishment, because we did not know of anyone in the Anderson family who had ever gone that far in college.

23
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:30,000
So my household anyway was one that recognized the value and the importance of education. And so they stressed that to the three of us, I'd one brother, one sister.

24
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:40,000
Well, maybe we would have been somewhat hesitant to go ahead and we not had to push, but it was not even a discussion in my home. You're going to college.

25
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:47,000
We don't care what you study, you can study farming, you can study singing, you can study whatever, but you're going to college.

26
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:58,000
But the town of America's itself, you could define segregation and discrimination by America's Georgia. There was no such thing as an integration.

27
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:09,000
The school system was totally separate. You could not have a sandwich in the lunch counter. There were no public transportation vehicles and any kind.

28
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:22,000
So that was not an issue that were totally segregated facilities, gas stations, what department stores were there that were segregated facilities.

29
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:33,000
School was totally segregated. So I'm saying that it was almost like two worlds in one, a black world and a white world.

30
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:41,000
I guess I did not complain that much because I'd not know any better until later on I volunteered to go into the Navy.

31
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:57,000
But if you look back on it now and you say, well, how could you possibly tolerate those kinds of conditions where you could be walking down the street and the white world would be coming toward you and say, Nigger, get off the sidewalk. You're where I want to walk.

32
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:02,000
And I would get off the sidewalk and let him have it.

33
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:13,000
How could you tolerate conditions whereby in your school system anyway, that was an elementary school and high school, but we all recognize we never got a new book.

34
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:21,000
We always had used books, secondhand books that have been written in and sometimes torn up.

35
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:26,000
That was a movie house in town, totally segregated again.

36
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:35,000
The likes had to sit in what we referred to as the buzzard roost up high. You had to go any separate entrance.

37
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:49,000
So those were the kinds of conditions that existed and were tolerated, if not accepted, certainly not light, but they were tolerated primarily because we did not know any other way.

38
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:58,000
So as I tried to figure out a way to get out of that situation, so number one, I elected to go to college.

39
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:07,000
My brother preceded me and he had joined the college. So he had already set the stage, the oldest of the three and he went to college.

40
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:13,000
Morehouse college also. Don't know whether he ever got a degree on that and that again is not important.

41
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:23,000
I went to college at Fort Valley State. I was probably attracted there more by having the opportunity to play football than to get a good education. That was secondary.

42
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:33,000
But somewhere in the back of my mind though, I always wanted to be a doctor. I always wanted to be a doctor. So I knew I had to get a college education if I was going to be a doctor.

43
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:38,000
So went to Fort Valley for two years and then World War II broke out.

44
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:43,000
Let me ask before you talk about the war. How did your family afford to send you and your brother to college?

45
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:57,000
They couldn't. Well, it did not cost like it cost today. This will amaze you. The tuition room and board at Fort Valley State College was $25 a month.

46
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:15,000
I worked to earning the extra money that I had. I worked as an assistant male carrier. I worked in the in the yard. What was the cafeteria part time?

47
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:37,000
I was a student and I drove for the president. Let me interject this parenthetically. The president of Fort Valley State College was born. His name was he was the father of Julian Bond, Horace Mann-Bahn, and educator, a renowned educator.

48
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:52,000
He was writing about education for blacks throughout the South. He selected me to be a driver. Mind you, 16 years old now. I started college at 15, but by 16 I had a license and was driving for the president.

49
00:07:52,000 --> 00:08:05,000
Taking care of his two children. He had a born and a girl. Julian Bond was one of them. But anyway, I did not realize the advantage that I had over millions and millions of other blacks.

50
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:20,000
I was in the presence of Horace Mann-Bahn, who was one of the premier black educators in the United States. He traveled throughout Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, studying education for blacks.

51
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:35,000
I traveled with Horace Mann-Bahn. I drove for him. There was no public transportation. Of course, there was no airplanes. Of course, bus transportation was very limited. So in it place we went, you drove, and I drove for him.

52
00:08:35,000 --> 00:09:01,000
So when the war broke out, though, and I was at home on the weekend, that's America's only about 70 miles from Fort Valley State. When the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor, the local newspaper, the America's Times Recorder, will never forget, had a front page headline, and they came out with an extra. And you heard them shouting on the streetcorders, I had never heard that in my life.

53
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:30,000
The Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor. I felt personally attacked. I was living in a society that was totally segregated, discrimination everywhere. I was hated to clans with threatened all of it. But I lived in that environment yet. When the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor, I felt so they had attacked me personally. They had attacked my family personally.

54
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:55,000
The next day, I tried to volunteer for the Army. I was 14. My mother stopped it, of course, she said, no, no. So I could not get in. But she waited a year, so when I approached 16, she finally said, he's going to get in the military in one way or the other. And I volunteered for the Navy.

55
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:06,000
But I did not know what I was volunteering for. It's interesting because I just wanted to get in the military. I would have been a Tuskegee Airman if they'd taken me.

56
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:17,000
But since I couldn't get to be a Tuskegee Airman, my mother wouldn't sign. I went to a recruiting station, and as I wanted to join, they said, well, we have two branch observers. We have the Army and the Navy.

57
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:30,000
I had heard about the Army, and I had seen the Army. I had seen them crawling around on the bellies, get shot at, under barbed wire. And I said, I don't want that. Let me have the other one. And they said, oh, there's a Navy. I said, I'll take it.

58
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:45,000
Then I was told there are two branches of the Navy. There's a Siemens branch, and there's a Stuart's branch. I don't know anything about either one. All I know is, I want to get in the military. I want to get at those Japanese that attacked my home.

59
00:10:45,000 --> 00:11:05,000
So I'll explain it to you. The Stuart's take care of the captain's quarters. They do the cooking. They do the cleaning. I said stop right there. I don't care if the other one is shoveling horse manure. I have not joined in the military to be anybody's servant. I've had that. So I became a Siemens.

60
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Let me take it back for just a minute. Okay. To this feeling you have after in December of 41 after Pro Harbour. It's very interesting to see you're saying you live in a world that's so sharply racially segregated. And if you feel personally engaged by this war question, any reflection on that sense of identification even amidst context that's as difficult as it was.

61
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:44,000
I equate that to the response of some slaves when they were told the emancipation proclamation has been signed. You're free. They said free to do what?

62
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:55,000
This is the only home I've ever known. There's the only family I've ever known. Oh, master takes pretty good care of me. I'm not going to leave this freedom.

63
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:13,000
So as bad as it was in segregation and discrimination and it was horrible, it was the only home that I knew. So yes, I was willing to take up arms to protect a society that wouldn't slave me.

64
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:22,000
Tell me about any recollections of your time on the service that really stand out maybe in a way that's racially infuctive.

65
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:38,000
I look back now and knew it was by design. I did not recognize it initially. But my company was the last all black company to go into the United States Navy.

66
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:49,000
Not a single member of my company that was 75 in my company. Not a single one of them had less than high school education. That was unprecedented. I didn't realize it at the time.

67
00:12:49,000 --> 00:13:04,000
I mean, I was 16 years old. I didn't know about the economic climate, the cultural climate, the educational climate. But as one later on, everyone in my company had not less than a high school education.

68
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:15,000
We were the most educated company in the United States Navy. We were a test who orchestrated that test. I don't know who planned it, but Secretary of the Navy.

69
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:30,000
I don't know, but we were a test. My company then excelled because we knew after a while that we were a test. We integrated a battalion, the first black company to integrate a battalion. This was a great leaks.

70
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:41,000
We excelled again because somehow another our parents had instilled in all of us. You've got to be better. You cannot be just as good as whites. You've got to be better.

71
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:56,000
Everybody in my company excelled. So I know they had another opportunity when I finished my basic training. I was home only leave and had tons of lightest would you believe today?

72
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:39,000
I was relieved. I was happy that I missed my tour of duty. And so I was put on private duty. You're going out anywhere. You're going out there to fight the Japanese anyway. So they put me on a ship.

73
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:55,000
And they made me a part of the seventh fleet under on the Joseph Orman on the Bull Horsley. I went out with the seventh fleet. They stopped in the Philippines for a few days. No, no. In Hawaii and islands for a few days. And then they dropped me off in the Philippines Island down in the late A.G.F.

74
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:05,000
There I think they forgot about me. The war had just recently come to an end. However, the word had not gotten out to all of these remote islands that the war is over.

75
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:18,000
So there were Japanese soldiers in the palm trees. And we said that they put them up there with a sack of rice and gave them a gun. And so just stay here and shoot everything that comes near.

76
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:33,000
So there was still some time in those trees even a year after the war had ended. So when I got out there just before we got off the ship, the captain of the ship said there's a shortage of hospital courmin.

77
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:46,000
Anyone who has any background at all in medicine report to the deck. I had two years of pre-mad. I reported. He said, okay, we're going to send you to hospital course school.

78
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:55,000
There were about a half a dozen of us who had a little bit of background at least in pre-mad. And we went to hospital course school for six weeks in the Philippine Islands.

79
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:07,000
We became doctors in six weeks. We don't know why it takes doctors so long now. But we became doctors in six weeks because hospital courmined worldly primary care physicians of the military.

80
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:17,000
So for the next year I took care of Sherbus men in the military. I always wore gun, of course. I didn't have to shoot anybody. But everybody out there was armed.

81
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:22,000
And that experience really confirmed your desire to go forward with medical career.

82
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:30,000
If they had been ever ined out in my mind as to whether I wanted to be a doctor or not, that would have confirmed it. I enjoyed that to no end.

83
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:36,000
How did you find your path forward towards medical education?

84
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:49,000
Now I'm convinced that I want to be a doctor. When I got out of the Navy, I went back to college. I met this wonderful woman that I eventually married.

85
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:59,000
She said, I was a big man on campus and she was just a lonely freshman. But anyway, I met her and I started to playing for medical school.

86
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:13,000
In those days, you did not have to have a degree. I finished two years of college in what constituted pre-mad. And I applied to every medical school in the United States and Canada.

87
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:24,000
I was turned down for several reasons. One Fort Bad Estate college was not recognized. It was not accredited by any accredited agency. None.

88
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:35,000
It was a very small school. There were 300 students total, not 300 in class, 300 students, 26 boys and all the rest of girls, difficult for boys.

89
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:42,000
But that was the situation as it was. So I got turned down by all of these colleges.

90
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:54,000
I was eligible for some GI Bill, two years. But there was a time when you either had to be in school or you would lose some of that credit.

91
00:17:54,000 --> 00:18:07,000
So I moved up to Atlanta with my new wife, who I met Martin Luther King, Jr. And that was prophetic. I did not plan that. He was not Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. then. He was just Marty.

92
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:15,000
He was a high school student. He was high school senior. He was graduating the year when up there. And he and my wife's brother were very good friends, very close friends.

93
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:27,000
Again, prophetic that I would meet the man who would eventually come to the world's leader. When both of us, I was one year older than Martin, we met in Atlanta because I married the right girl.

94
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:35,000
But while I was waiting now to get into medical school, I had to be in some kind of school. So I went to March your San School of all things.

95
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:47,000
Because the March your San College curriculum was almost the same as pre-med curriculum for the second and third year. And probably as much as the third and fourth year.

96
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:59,000
If you can imagine the March your San College having anatomy, physiology, chemistry, pathology, but those were the courses that were being offered. So wow, I said this would prepare me for medical school.

97
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:15,000
So got that degree and would have stayed in Atlanta to get my college degree except that a federal director or him, federal home owner in Montgomery by the name of Loveless invited me on a mere position in Montgomery.

98
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:29,000
And he said, if you come here, get your college degree and you can work whenever you want to set your own schedule. I'll pay you $15 a week. Set your own schedule. I could not turn that down.

99
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:39,000
I went to Montgomery again, prophetic. Who did I meet in Montgomery at Montgomery State College, Ralph David Abinathy.

100
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:55,000
Not the right Reverend Dr. Ralph David Abinathy, just David Abinathy, schoolmate, and we became very good friends. I think he and my wife were closer than you can imagine because he spent a lot of time at my home while I was working.

101
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:03,000
I was working at your home, going to school, I'd come home. My wife had fixed him, my dinner, he ate my dinner and she'd have to start all over again.

102
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:23,000
But he was as close as her brother. He became the Godfather of our oldest child. That's how close we were. So working at the funeral home, I was able to take enough classes that I graduated from Montgomery from Alabama State College. It was called by the way, Alabama State College for Negroes.

103
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:40,000
Well, people look at me and they have to wonder, you see a Negro or a white. So what we would do as the bus would leave Montgomery going north on one of our tours, we black out the Fronigros on the side of the bus. That was a joke around there.

104
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:51,000
But anyway, I got my degree from Alabama State College for Negroes and I was offered a job back in Atlanta at the College of Mercury Science.

105
00:20:51,000 --> 00:21:04,000
There, I'm still I'm trying to get into medical school. My eye was on the prize, eyes on the prize. I'm trying to get a medical school. So now I took some graduate studies at Atlanta University working toward a master's.

106
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:20,000
I was singing in a radio choir at Queen Street Church. One morning, we were broadcasting from this television studio in Atlanta and a local radio station.

107
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:36,000
WERD, we called it the Good Words station. The program director, Ken Knight, I will never forget him. He called the radio station where I was broadcasting from and said, would you be interested in a career in radio?

108
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:48,000
Oh no, I'm going to be a doctor. He said in case you change your mind, come back to see me. So one Sunday afternoon, I had nothing else to do, couldn't get in medical school. Then I'm going down to visit this guy in radio.

109
00:21:48,000 --> 00:22:09,000
I went down there and said, would you mind reading a couple of passes this? Okay, I read it. He says, you know, you could do a right radio. I said, all right, I'll try it out. So I became a radio announcer every afternoon for two hours. I was with a guy named Ali Pat, his name was James.

110
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:19,000
Oh, got his last name now. We call him Ali Pat Patrick, it was his name James Patrick and James Patrick, me still be doing radio in Atlanta.

111
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:34,000
But there is where I got the experience in radio. The background in in Mercury, Slance at the Mercury, Slance School, why did you do all of those things? You want to be a doctor?

112
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:46,000
Again, prophetic. When I finally got accepted in medical school and it was only because of a friend of my father, he was a physician practicing in Albany.

113
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:59,000
Albany, we consider that a sub-rebror of America's with vice-versa, but my dad was an insurance man. I said in his office, wasn't Albany. He was district manager of the North Carolina Mutual Life Insurance Company.

114
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:14,000
And his office was in Albany and so I would go to Albany on occasion. And he says, why don't you meet my doctor who is a graduate of the Demoan Steel College of osteopathy?

115
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:25,000
Well, I was curious. And I had that academic curiosity. I want you to know, what is osteopathy? I went to the dictionary and found it had to do with bones.

116
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:34,000
So I told him, I don't want to do that, daddy. I want to be a real doctor. I want to give shot to little babies, do surgery. I want to be a real doctor.

117
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:45,000
So finally he convinced me to come, at least meet Dr. Williger Reese. I was respectful of my father. He was a man of small statue, only about 5253.

118
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:56,000
And I was about 5,000-11, but I never challenged my father. So I went to see, to visit this doctor Reese. He had the biggest practice in town.

119
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:05,000
He was doing minus surgery. He was delivering babies. He was giving shots. He was writing prescriptions. He said, what that? That's all they ever wanted to do.

120
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:17,000
He's not trying to tell you that you idiot. He could do that because he was my father. But Williger Reese was doing everything that a black doctor could do in the real South.

121
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:31,000
Black doctors had no hospital privileges. So Reese happened to be a graduate of what was the Demoan Steel College of osteopathy. It is now Demoan University.

122
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:41,000
He knew the dean because he had a degree in biochemistry before he went to the College of osteopathy medicine and they needed an instructor in biochemistry.

123
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:50,000
So they made a deal with him. He had an MD degree that he could not use because it was from a school in New York that lost its accreditation.

124
00:24:50,000 --> 00:25:02,000
So a degree that could not be used, he couldn't get a license. So to see if you come here to teach biochemistry, you can then take courses in osteopathic medicine. You can get a degree in osteopathic medicine.

125
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:13,000
Now you can get a license. You can practice. Good deal all the way around. So he called a dean and he says, the son of my best friend wants to become a doctor. Will you give him a chance?

126
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:31,000
Oh, if he's a friend of your best friend, yeah. So I went up to Demoan and this was back in 1952. I took the interest exams on that trip or higher reading comprehension and Minnesota multitasking.

127
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:43,000
I passed them both and was accepted on the spot. I have never ever looked back. One of the best decisions that had ever been made for me, mind you, for me.

128
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:57,000
Because osteopathic profession has just, it has grown phenomenally from sixth colleges to now thirty colleges, from fifteen osteopathic physicians to seventy five thousand.

129
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:07,000
And I had the privilege of becoming the president of the American Hospital Association. So I'm saying, I could never have planned this life out.

130
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:15,000
Everything along the way, been married to a lady who made me friends with Martin Luther King, Jr.

131
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:22,000
Winded up in March of his slain school, I learned how to be a mortician that helped me to pay my tuition and get through medical school.

132
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:33,000
This radio program that got me into the living room, it also helped me to get through medical school because in Demoan, I was a radio announcer and I was a mortician.

133
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:43,000
I prepared the cadavers for the medical school and I had a radio program that started out. It was what was called the ethnic hour.

134
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:56,000
One hour, one day a week, they had four segments, Polish, Western, Negro, and something else. And it was losing money.

135
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:03,000
So I went by the radio station and I told the manager, I needed a job in radio, I had some experience.

136
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:10,000
Third thing for you, I said, but you've got this one hour program of ethnic music. I said, I can do that program.

137
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:19,000
He said, it's not making any money. I'll make your offer. I will do the program for free. I will go out and sell the ads.

138
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:26,000
If it does not make any money, don't pay me. He said, are you nuts? A little bit. A little bit.

139
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:37,000
Okay, I'll give you a chance. After about two or three months, the program went from one hour, one day a week to four hours every night.

140
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:47,000
I started his incentives as much time as I wanted. A program that I had labeled Gala time, every night eight to twelve.

141
00:27:47,000 --> 00:28:02,000
I'd get off radio station twelve o'clock. I had called the record back because in those days, the radio announcer was everything. He was radio announcer, he was the engineer, he was the newscaster, he was sportscaster. I did it all. I was the only one in studio.

142
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:11,000
I would get done about one o'clock, then I would go and study the rest of the night and be ready to go to class the next morning.

143
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:13,000
The project is to set.

144
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:14,000
Paul.

145
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:29,000
We're back after a short break. Dr. Anderson, we were talking about Des Moines and your work, you've been this tremendous success, really transforming this radio hour into a very, very substantial program Gala time.

146
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:38,000
Could you touch on, could you touch on racial questions inside that framework at all? Did you?

147
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:49,000
Let's start with when I first, now the interview took place several months before school started, started like in September.

148
00:28:50,000 --> 00:29:07,000
There were social, civic, academic, scholarly organizations on campus. One of them was called the Square and Compass Club, the Masons.

149
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:16,000
And when I was a student at Alabama State College having little to do, I joined the Masons.

150
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:19,000
And so I figured a Mason is a Mason.

151
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:26,000
So when I found out that there was a chapter on campus, I went to join it.

152
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:33,000
And they said, you can't join. What do you mean? I'm a Mason. Here's my current. I'm a Mason. Do you play Mason?

153
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:48,000
Yeah, but you came from a clandestine Masonic organization. What do you mean, clandestine? You mean I'm colored? Well, pretty much so.

154
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:56,000
You don't belong with the real Masons. You're all outside, Joe Mason.

155
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:10,000
So I did not buck that. I did not challenge that. They had never heard of Martin Luther King Jr. or several movements. So I did not want to get put out of school. So I went along with it.

156
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:22,000
The other thing that happened was the dean thinking that he was doing something to my benefit said to me, Anderson, this is the morning.

157
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:36,000
The races do not mix very well here. You're not to date any white women. You're not to socialize with any white women.

158
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:50,000
That became almost an albatross for me because at one of the official school functions, the chairman of the Bell chemistry department happened to be female, a white female, mind you.

159
00:30:50,000 --> 00:31:03,000
She had a couple of drinks, I think. But something told her to tell one of my classmates to go and get me and bring me to her because she weren't there with me.

160
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:18,000
Now, what would you do if I dance with her? I'll be put out of school by the dean, the dean's already told me that. If I don't dance with her, I'm going to flink by her chemistry and I'll be put out of school. What a dilemma.

161
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:38,000
Well, I had another beer and I went in dance with her. Nothing happened. The school didn't collapse. No race for war broke out. I was not put out of school. I was not even calling to the dean's office.

162
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:54,000
There was a fear that some people had that if there is integration, it would prove to be disastrous. The world would come to an end if white and blikes mix. Nothing happened.

163
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:07,000
I can say in retrospect that was the beginning of desegregation of the city of the White Iowa. There was a very popular pizza parlour. They are known as babes pizza.

164
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:32,000
If anybody who had been in the moorin, if they were there as much as 55 or 60 years ago, they knew about babes pizza. A very popular hangout for school kids, college kids, especially from the moorin school college of osteopathy, except that no blacks. They were not served a black.

165
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:59,000
Did I run into it? Even in Des Moines, I was there for the interview. I stayed at the YMCA. Incidentally, that ingratiated me to the YMCA because the YMCA was one of the few places in the United States that never had segregation.

166
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:10,000
That is why once I finished medical school and started into practice, I started raising money for the YMCA. Do it till today.

167
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:14,000
Did the moorin have an active NAACP chapter?

168
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:27,000
Yes. When you say active, active, but very small and not taken on many projects. There were two or three people who were active in trying to desegregate the city of the moorin.

169
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:36,000
Did you go to the moorin during Brown vs. Board of Education? That was 54. It was leading up to Brown vs. Board of Education, right?

170
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:41,000
You were there 52-56. Brown? The Montgomery Bus Boycott?

171
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:51,000
The Montgomery Bus Boycott was 56. I was graduating. I graduated being 56. We went on though for the entire year, 56 up to 57.

172
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:54,000
Until smart and we're somewhere 55?

173
00:33:54,000 --> 00:34:01,000
But remember though, word did not travel around as fast as you might expect.

174
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:11,000
Newspaper articles from Montgomery never got to the moorin. Nobody in the moorin as I knew ever subscribed to the New York Times or the Washington Post.

175
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:15,000
Television within its infancy, so very rare few people had televisions.

176
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:24,000
So it was sort of like the emancipation proclamation was signed in January, but they did not find out about it.

177
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:31,000
In Arkansas until June. The same thing was true pretty much even in 1952.

178
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:41,000
1956, 1954. Yeah, the schools have been desegregated, but the word didn't get around. The day when it was signed, it did not happen overnight.

179
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:50,000
Did you have a feeling on leaving Des Moines moving ahead with your life you wanted to Michigan for a year of internship?

180
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:51,000
Yes.

181
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:59,000
That you were going to put your hands on this question of trying to change the social realities? Was that in your spirit at that time?

182
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:03,000
Well, let's prioritize my life.

183
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:04,000
Sure.

184
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:22,000
I had an ultimate objective was to become a doctor. And I took a lot of things to become a doctor, including the internship that I got in Flint came about as a result of the same dean, John B. Schumaker, who said the races don't mix.

185
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:31,000
You are not the socialized with white women in Des Moines. That same dean though after I've been there for three years, fourth year.

186
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:38,000
I needed to get an internship and Flint, I still had the hospital had one of the best internships in the country.

187
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:49,000
He personally got on the phone and called administrator Keith Balker will never forget him either. He called him and he says, I've got this colored doctor.

188
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:57,000
He's a fine student. He's not a troublemaker and he will make a fine intern for you.

189
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:15,000
This was unprecedented. I had to go out for personal interview before I could get a clinical clerkship there. What if a person interview and the House Fair Training Committee that selects interns call a special meeting just for me?

190
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:24,000
They interviewed me because they could not challenge my credentials academically because I was in the top 10% of my class.

191
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:36,000
I was one man there in family practice who says, I don't even know why we're here. I moved that we accept this man as an intern. I was sitting there and never ever done that other people.

192
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:44,000
I think he put them on the spot because they could not think of a good reason to deny me. They couldn't. I was accepted.

193
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:56,000
The first black to ever get training outside of a college-owned hospital in history that was 1955 when I went there.

194
00:36:56,000 --> 00:36:59,000
Passing in.

195
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:10,000
What's up for just a second? We're back after short break. What drew you back to Albany in 1957?

196
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:22,000
My wife. It was not the lure of going back into this cesspool of segregation and discrimination. I was not going back there to change the world.

197
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:36,000
Martin Luther King, Jr., was lived known. I knew him personally but in terms of his potential as a world leader was not well known in 1956 and 1957.

198
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:49,000
We had just come out of the Montgomery bus work cut and all the other places in the south where this might have happened. It's not going to happen here. It happened in Montgomery but it's not going to happen here.

199
00:37:49,000 --> 00:38:05,000
So it was not my intent to go in there and become a rabble rouser and start desegregating Albany. What happened was my wife and I met a couple that were professors at the University of Michigan Flint campus.

200
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:22,000
We had a good and ginger edwards. Very well educated people. Both PhDs. We became friends. They got to know us very well because they had a couple of young kids and of course we had a couple of young kids. We had three I guess. They had four or they had five.

201
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:34,000
Anyway, we had some kids and we would get together frequently. We didn't have much money so we didn't go out to clubs or anything like that. We would just go to each other's homes and we'd have dinner and we'd sit around and talk.

202
00:38:34,000 --> 00:38:46,000
I say television was still in this infancy so we would talk. Can you imagine a group of people just sitting around and talking for three or four hours. That's what we did. So they got to know us very well.

203
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:57,000
Nearing the end of my internship and now I'm in the process of deciding where I'm now to what a practice. In those days that's all you need. Internship you could practice.

204
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:10,000
There was a group of surgeons at Finosibatic Hospital. D'Aderian was a key one. Slocke of D'Aderian. He and his partner said to me,

205
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:22,000
we'd like to set you up in practice in Flint. We were fine and she was setting up in practice. His partner was named Taviner. Taviner and D'Aderian.

206
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:35,000
They said we don't want you to bury yourself and they use those words. Bury yourself in the colored neighborhood. We want you to at least get on a border street because we feel based on our experiences with you.

207
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:42,000
You're going to have as many white patients as you have black patients. So be prepared to take both. It was a good advice. That's all.

208
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:50,000
Because in all humility I said I was the best intern and they have a head. But later on they wouldn't give me a residency in surgery.

209
00:39:50,000 --> 00:40:01,000
And that was the bit of, that's the ulterior motive there because they thought I would have a good practice and because they have set me up in practice I would refer my surgery to them.

210
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:16,000
And I would have. But my wife in one of these conversations with Bird and Ginger Edwards. She says, we're going to go back and talk to Bird and Ginger again.

211
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:25,000
You want to stay here to practice because you can have a great practice right off from day one. But you made a promise.

212
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:45,000
What was that? You said if you ever got your education you were going back down south. The rural south where they need you. They don't need you in Flint. I said damn. This woman remembers everything.

213
00:40:45,000 --> 00:41:02,000
And she had women have that phenomenal memory. You know of selective memory. The thing that wants to remember. And just the same way I could tell you every bad thing I've ever done in my life. But she did remember before I even got into medical school.

214
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:08,000
You said if I ever got my education I was going back.

215
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:19,000
So we were talking with Bird and Ginger Edwards. They sent me to another room. She talked with me. Go back. Sit Bird and Ginger go back.

216
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:26,000
So the last time I went to talk to Bird and Ginger they said pack your bag. You're going back.

217
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:31,000
We're putting Ginger wider. Like like.

218
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:38,000
Yeah, exceptional. They said you going back. They knew this.

219
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:51,000
As much as I challenged my wife. I can say in retrospect every major decision I ever made in our entire six or one years of marriage was made by my wife.

220
00:41:51,000 --> 00:42:07,000
The decision to marry her. And just I said I didn't propose to her. She told me what she told one of her college friends when she first met me she said I'm a Mary. I didn't know it.

221
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:20,000
But it was it was it was that woman who got me to know Martin Luther King which resulted in me ultimately becoming a part of a major civil movement. That's my wife.

222
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:25,000
What's talking more about her? I want to talk more about her very much.

223
00:42:25,000 --> 00:42:30,000
So against your first instinct you went back to Albany in 1957.

224
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:46,000
It wasn't exactly to Albany. As a matter of fact I looked around. I did not know for sure where I worked at practice. I thought about my hometown because they had it was segregated but there was a public wing to the hospital.

225
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:58,000
I was fighting two things being an osteopathic physician which was you and number in Georgia and being black limited my opportunities to get hospital privileges anywhere.

226
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:15,000
But the need of hospital code wing in America. But in Albany there was no such black patients were put in the basement where they had to compete with the laundry room and the furnishings and the stained pipes.

227
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:22,000
But then I went to several of the small towns and they all had an interest in having a doctor.

228
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:35,000
If they were willing to accept the segregated conditions that existed and the other hurdle was getting over you the being an osteopathic physician and they were not well known in those days.

229
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:47,000
So what prompted me to settle in Albany my father's office was there so he knew everybody in town everybody knew him. So it was not like I had to be introduced.

230
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:56,000
But the one that convinced me more than anyone else was CB King or 20 CB King. He and I, we had known each other for many years.

231
00:43:56,000 --> 00:44:06,000
My dad was in Albany and I would go down that period and I knew the King family. He had a very outstanding family.

232
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:19,000
So in his office I remember when he finally convinced me he said to me he called me Andy Andy. All of them will be as good to you as you are to it.

233
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:31,000
That said to me if I put forth the effort if I give these people good service they take care of me. That made up my mind for me.

234
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:42,000
And then when a Jorese who was still in practice he was getting somewhat up in age when you got in the middle of 50s it was up in age in those days because I was just barely out of my 20s.

235
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:55,000
But Bill Reese who was also in practice there said to me you can come in with me if you so desire or if you want to do it on your own I was happy in any way I can to get you started.

236
00:44:55,000 --> 00:45:10,000
Well what else could I want? The lead in lawyer, how to regard it and one of the business doctors in town then it was settled. That's why elected to go to Albany.

237
00:45:10,000 --> 00:45:14,000
Did the practice unfold in those first couple years pretty pretty smooth?

238
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:29,000
They were standing at my door waiting again and before I get over my doors even I made a mistake actually being pressured by some people who knew I was there to start treating them before I completed an examination.

239
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:39,000
I had not set up a laboratory didn't do any laboratory tests and I start treating them and I missed a diagnosis of diabetes that I never should have missed if I just been doing my routine.

240
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:52,000
Of course everybody came in you know got a routine you're the now routine but I'm saying that I was resting the practice but the day it was announced my office was open the office will full all day every day.

241
00:45:52,000 --> 00:46:08,000
I would see as many as a hundred patients a day I never lacked for patients. So if I was doing so well in practice why would I get involved in civil rights? That was not my intent either.

242
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:19,000
I guess one quick question turned to that. All right. So the stream of patients who came through your door would not have been just from the city of Albany or all around.

243
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:29,000
Yeah. Okay. So you you would have not not that you didn't know this already but you would have seen in the health circumstances of your patients the reflection of the material conditions.

244
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:41,000
I was amazed at how inadequate the healthcare was that these people getting. Now there were two black doctors there.

245
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:58,000
One was had a limited practice by his choosing and Elvin was really joeries who I said was getting up an age some and wanted to cut back some so actually they resulted to go into right doctors even when they didn't want to because that's all had available.

246
00:46:58,000 --> 00:47:08,000
But in doing that they had to go in the back door sit in a separate waiting room and wait until all the white patients had been seen.

247
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:36,000
Some of the black patients told me stories that were just unimaginable like for example they have several black patients come into office at the same time not in the exam room in the office and they would sit around the table and the doctor was sitting behind his death and what's wrong with you boy and what's wrong with you boy and what's wrong with your girl and make his diagnosis and make out the prescription based on that kind of examination.

248
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:46,000
Some of these patients in chronic congestive heart failure had to come in once a week to get a shot of mercury hydrant which was a diuretic.

249
00:47:46,000 --> 00:48:05,000
All these people needed was whole leaf digit tell us plain digit tell us it's been around for a hundred years those were the kind of patients that I was seeing when I got there and said I had to hard back to what my wife said these people need you and you don't need to be.

250
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:15,000
And I but I am saying you don't need to be a major surgeon you just need to be a good old country doctor that listen to the people and give them just basic stuff.

251
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:24,000
Give them digit tell us give them incident things that they weren't getting.

252
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:27,000
Some imagine what a difficulty paying.

253
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:42,000
That's an understatement my office fee was three dollars home calls five dollars when I could get it I never turned anybody down.

254
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:48,000
I put a lot of money on the books but also I never was hungry.

255
00:48:48,000 --> 00:49:06,000
They would bring me a ham a chicken eggs whether they had I delivered babies for fifty dollars pre-natal that they never got because they never came in delivery postnatal fifty dollars.

256
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:18,000
In other words I didn't get rich I was never going to get rich fractured down there however I never in hungry I never missed a house note I never missed a car note.

257
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:34,000
And so when I did get involved in silver rights and they got a little bit ahead of stirring to let you know though when I said to these people follow me to jail a thousand people follow me to jail why.

258
00:49:34,000 --> 00:50:03,000
They did not know what the future would hold they did not know how long they'll be in jail whether get bailed out whether I'm lawyers they went because they trusted their doctor they trusted that doctor I don't think they would have done that it if I had not had that kind of relationship with them so I did alright I was even buying for it automobile eventually bought over this station wagon however they were running to the ground because we ran a.

259
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:10,000
Carp whore during the breakouts.

260
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:13,000
I just lost my question.

261
00:50:13,000 --> 00:50:22,000
I'll come back to it in the in the late 50s.

262
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:25,000
What was did you and your family remember the church?

263
00:50:25,000 --> 00:50:26,000
Oh yeah.

264
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:31,000
We went to all been we went to my father's church.

265
00:50:31,000 --> 00:50:33,000
He had a church then he had a church in America.

266
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:37,000
The church in America is a pastor his church in all been it was my Zion.

267
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:39,000
My Zion Baptist church.

268
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:49,000
It's pastor was E. James Grant who was about 90 years old then but one of the most courageous men I have ever known.

269
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:59,000
Courageous in the sense that he would be a pastor on Sundays but he was principal of a school in Baker County during the week.

270
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:10,000
Baker County had the reputation of being the most racist the most violent county in the end time South.

271
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:15,000
Bikes were known to go to jail down they had never heard from again.

272
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:25,000
It had such a terrible reputation that even white people from the South were reluctant to drive through Newton which was in Baker County.

273
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:29,000
I got on the staff at a small hospital 50 miles away from Albany.

274
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:31,000
It was down in Bainbridge, Georgia.

275
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:34,000
A little hospital owned by black doctor 50 beds.

276
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:43,000
He was a soul doctor only doctor he did everything and he said that if your patients are willing to travel you have privileges right here.

277
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:46,000
And so I said what privilege do I have?

278
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:51,000
He said you have a license don't you oh I have a license that's your privilege.

279
00:51:51,000 --> 00:52:00,000
And so the patients of mine who needed to be hospitalized needed some surgery who willing to travel to Bainbridge we would go there but I had to travel through Newton.

280
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:09,000
And I was a non-violent person mind you but I did have a pistol-pottist permit because I used to make house calls in strange places.

281
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:16,000
I never knew when the clan was going to decide well doc you've done enough we're going to hang you today.

282
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:20,000
So I would put a pistol on the seat of my car as I would drive through Newton.

283
00:52:20,000 --> 00:52:26,000
And I said I would accept a ticket if they if I'd stop I would take a ticket but I was not going to jail.

284
00:52:26,000 --> 00:52:35,000
And you hate to take the kind of fatalistic attitude but I was not going to go today because I knew too many people who have been lynched.

285
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:38,000
I have to be arrested in Newton.

286
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:43,000
Did you ever did you ever patients come in who had been victims of white violence?

287
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:44,000
Oh God yes.

288
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:45,000
Oh yeah.

289
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:48,000
This was not just a occasional thing this was not in frequent.

290
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:50,000
Oh no.

291
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:58,000
As a matter of fact the clan held its rallies one had blocked from my home.

292
00:52:58,000 --> 00:53:07,000
I could go on my backyard and see the flaming cross and see the hood at Clansman and yelling their epithets.

293
00:53:07,000 --> 00:53:17,000
I could hear that they were very close and blacks who would get arrested were very often very frequently beaten up.

294
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:26,000
As a matter of fact the lawyer himself, C.B. Kane, was going into the jail to visit one of his clients and was beaten by the sheriff himself.

295
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:28,000
So was it common?

296
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:31,000
A lawyer yet beaten by the sheriff?

297
00:53:31,000 --> 00:53:37,000
I meant in course after 61 even prior in your first couple of years in Albany.

298
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:40,000
Did you see people come in as patients?

299
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:41,000
Not that many.

300
00:53:41,000 --> 00:53:42,000
Not that many.

301
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:43,000
No that many.

302
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:44,000
Right.

303
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:55,000
I want to ask two about the local and the way CP and the criterion club in those years for everything really accelerated.

304
00:53:55,000 --> 00:54:00,000
And the Urban League was there also at the Urban League.

305
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:05,000
And there were a couple of social clubs because the criterion club was a civic club.

306
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:12,000
And there was a woman's club called the Utrell, we call it a Utrell, but the Utrell is nature now.

307
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:19,000
It was like a one of Greek letters but there was some kind of a social club that women belonged to.

308
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:26,000
And let me say that and there were several neighborhoods that had organizations like the neighborhood that I lived in.

309
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:31,000
I think we called it the Cedar neighborhood.

310
00:54:31,000 --> 00:54:39,000
Anyway, there were neighborhoods that had names and the women primarily would be organized in these neighborhood groups.

311
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:47,000
And they would very often petition the city for things like pave industries, put in lights in, put in parks in.

312
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:50,000
That kind of activity is going on a long time.

313
00:54:50,000 --> 00:54:55,000
And the criterion club, I was a member of the Criterian Club periodically.

314
00:54:55,000 --> 00:55:00,000
We were just going meet with some of the city officials and there were some of the officials that would meet with you.

315
00:55:00,000 --> 00:55:02,000
They wouldn't do anything but they would meet with you.

316
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:05,000
Ase Kelly was the mayor.

317
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:11,000
And Ase Kelly was stretching a little bit.

318
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:18,000
He was probably fairly liberal, fairly liberal, as well as the chief of police, Larry Pritchett.

319
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:22,000
When I say they were fairly liberal, you could go and sit down and talk with them.

320
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:33,000
They could not do anything because they were held captive by this system of segregation and discrimination that demanded that they not do anything.

321
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:48,000
Ase Kelly on occasion had me to come to his office to talk because once the urban movement had been organized, we petitioned the mayor's office to establish a biracial commission.

322
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:52,000
The mayor had no power to do that.

323
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:55,000
I'll get to that.

324
00:55:56,000 --> 00:56:04,000
Going back, there were a number of liberal white people that the blacks could talk to.

325
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:11,000
There was a lady called Miss B. She was the owner, operator of Bob's candy.

326
00:56:11,000 --> 00:56:16,000
She took great pride in the fact that all of her workers were treated the same.

327
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:19,000
Black and white, the all were treated the same.

328
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:25,000
That was unheard of in any other business or industry in 1956.

329
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:32,000
And Miss B, she might still be a lab, she would be 90 or so, but she said very interesting lady.

330
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:38,000
And there were a few places like that, though, where blacks and whites were equally treated.

331
00:56:38,000 --> 00:56:46,000
I would guess, say, one like Miss B, she and any other emerging liberal-minded whites.

332
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:50,000
They did not have, may I speak publicly about that today?

333
00:56:50,000 --> 00:56:52,000
No, they couldn't.

334
00:56:52,000 --> 00:56:57,000
Matter of fact, Larry Pritchett at one point, this was at the height of the movement.

335
00:56:57,000 --> 00:56:59,000
He had me in his office.

336
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:04,000
He was as frustrated as anybody with his hand over his heart, said to me,

337
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:08,000
Is this the way you think you can make people like you?

338
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:15,000
And I said to him, Chief, you'll never know whether you can like me or not, as long as you've been kept apart.

339
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:18,000
This system keeps us apart.

340
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:21,000
He and I became the best of friends.

341
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:24,000
When it was over, we became the best of friends.

342
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:26,000
I want to ask you about that.

343
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:28,000
I just remember to come back to that point.

344
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:30,000
I'll tell you what happened to him. Go ahead.

345
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:38,000
February 1960, in the Greensboro City, and very soon, the wave of cities unfolds across the South.

346
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:45,000
We start to hear about, well, if the word to reach you, people would have heard a little bit about a group called SNCC.

347
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:48,000
The momentum is really gathering.

348
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:51,000
The freedom rise in 61.

349
00:57:51,000 --> 00:57:59,000
It's in 61, October 61, that a few young men from SNCC come down to.

350
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:03,000
Thank you for coming there.

351
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:06,000
Do you remember your first sense that something might be checked?

352
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:09,000
They came to town before October.

353
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:14,000
They came to town earlier, probably several months earlier, but it was very quiet.

354
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:23,000
Another way it's all they would do was, they would go to homes and ask them, would you register the boat?

355
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:29,000
Some of them, fearless ones, or you'll try it, knew they couldn't get it.

356
00:58:29,000 --> 00:58:35,000
But two or three people out of time would go with the SNCC people with an attempt to register the boat.

357
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:37,000
Of course, they never could get there.

358
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:43,000
The registrar was always on vacation or taking a 16 hour lunch break.

359
00:58:43,000 --> 00:58:49,000
I do believe they had done away with pole tax at the time, but they had not done away with literally sea tests.

360
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:52,000
But they would make that so difficult and nobody could pass.

361
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:57,000
So I'm saying it was just sparsely done like that over period of weeks.

362
00:58:57,000 --> 00:59:02,000
Then, since they weren't making any progress, they started demonstrations.

363
00:59:02,000 --> 00:59:12,000
And they went in the form of no more than three or four with signs, registered the boat, and they'd go downtown, and they would get arrested.

364
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:14,000
And that began to build.

365
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:16,000
And I saw that more and more.

366
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:23,000
And the more they tried to get people registered the more they would get arrested for the least thing.

367
00:59:23,000 --> 00:59:29,000
My office was in a section called Harlem, two blocks out of the heart of town.

368
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:36,000
Sitting at my desk in my office, I could see these kids going downtown, taking two or three people, and getting arrested.

369
00:59:36,000 --> 00:59:39,000
Getting yelled at, getting cursed.

370
00:59:39,000 --> 00:59:44,000
The black people who were getting registered the boat, being threatened and intimidated,

371
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:49,000
going to cancel out your mortgage, you're going to lose your job, and I got uncomfortable.

372
00:59:49,000 --> 00:59:51,000
That's going to hit me.

373
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:54,000
And I said to myself, they're doing that for me.

374
00:59:54,000 --> 01:00:01,000
They are trying to get people registered the boat for me, my family.

375
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:04,000
So that's when I got out there and joined them.

376
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:08,000
Tell me your first impressions of Charles Sharad,

377
01:00:08,000 --> 01:00:09,000
or Del Riga?

378
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:11,000
They were reckless.

379
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:13,000
They were fearless.

380
01:00:13,000 --> 01:00:19,000
But also in the Criterion Club, when we talk about it, we say, but they had nothing to lose.

381
01:00:19,000 --> 01:00:23,000
They had no jobs, they had no property, they had no money.

382
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:24,000
Then nothing to lose.

383
01:00:24,000 --> 01:00:26,000
All they had was dedication and commitment.

384
01:00:26,000 --> 01:00:28,000
That's all they had.

385
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:34,000
As a matter of fact, dying national at one point.

386
01:00:34,000 --> 01:00:38,000
When these people got in these demonstrations, they already had slammed their wheel and

387
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:39,000
asked to test them.

388
01:00:39,000 --> 01:00:46,000
In other words, if worse came to worse than they were killed, it was not totally unexpected.

389
01:00:46,000 --> 01:00:51,000
But anyway, my conscious was steried, really.

390
01:00:51,000 --> 01:00:53,000
My conscious was steried.

391
01:00:53,000 --> 01:01:00,000
And I said, took it to the Criterion Club first, and I said, we got to do something.

392
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:09,000
We have to get in front of these kids because we are their leaders to paraphrase Mahatma Gandhi.

393
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:12,000
So they then said, well, let's don't do it ourselves.

394
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:14,000
Let's get the other clubs together.

395
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:21,000
And that's when we call the meeting of the Criterion Club, NAACP, Urban League, the Uralis

396
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:22,000
Medirins.

397
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:24,000
And there might have been some other social clubs.

398
01:01:24,000 --> 01:01:28,000
We were called them together at the home of Ed Hamilton, who was a dentist.

399
01:01:28,000 --> 01:01:29,000
He's dead now.

400
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:36,000
And he was also courageous to open up his home for this meeting, but he knew we were being

401
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:39,000
watched by the police, by the FBI.

402
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:40,000
I don't know who else.

403
01:01:40,000 --> 01:01:42,000
But we organized there.

404
01:01:42,000 --> 01:01:46,000
I was elected president, not because I had inexperienced whatsoever.

405
01:01:46,000 --> 01:01:48,000
I had none in several rights.

406
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:52,000
But I think I was elected because of two things.

407
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:55,000
Number one, I did not depend on the white people from my living.

408
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:56,000
I depend on black patients.

409
01:01:57,000 --> 01:02:03,000
Number two, I had not been in all but in long enough to get any enemies among the blacks.

410
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:07,000
So your ideal, no enemies independent.

411
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:09,000
And also probably young enough to be...

412
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:10,000
Young enough to be...

413
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:12,000
You should be connected to the youth.

414
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:13,000
Mostly, yeah.

415
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:16,000
Because any better or with 30, could not be trusted by the youth.

416
01:02:16,000 --> 01:02:18,000
Yeah, just young enough that the youth would follow me.

417
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:19,000
Yeah.

418
01:02:19,000 --> 01:02:20,000
And that was the beginning.

419
01:02:20,000 --> 01:02:21,000
Yeah.

420
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:24,000
Can you say that this is very interesting, because obviously one of the key things in this repeats

421
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:27,000
in every, almost every place that you look at the close of the right history.

422
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:32,000
Of course there are different opinions and different factions that emerge in a community

423
01:02:32,000 --> 01:02:37,000
and by age, by economic position, et cetera, et cetera, philosophy.

424
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:45,000
In Albany, can you talk a little bit about the different perspectives and different groups and factions inside the black community,

425
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:51,000
particularly because there will be tensions, of course, you know, between different folks about how to proceed.

426
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:53,000
I think we had the extremes.

427
01:02:53,000 --> 01:02:54,000
We had those...

428
01:02:54,000 --> 01:02:55,000
What are you doing?

429
01:02:55,000 --> 01:02:58,000
You're disrupting the peace and tranquility of this.

430
01:02:58,000 --> 01:02:59,000
I'm going to lose my job.

431
01:02:59,000 --> 01:03:01,000
I'm going to lose my house.

432
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:03,000
Forklose my mortgage.

433
01:03:03,000 --> 01:03:05,000
And they stayed as far away from it as they could.

434
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:08,000
They never came to the intermediaries, no mass meetings, anything else.

435
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:10,000
That was at one extreme.

436
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:16,000
At the other extreme, there were those who were willing to throw caution to the wind as the past or mountain Zion.

437
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:22,000
I'm saying here's a man who depended on white races in Bechalca, California, living,

438
01:03:22,000 --> 01:03:27,000
yet he would open up his church for the mass meetings.

439
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:29,000
Those are the extreme.

440
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:34,000
There were some of those in the middle now that would give money.

441
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:37,000
They weren't about to know it.

442
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:43,000
That would be those who would come to the mass meetings, but they're not going to get in the march in demonstration.

443
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:47,000
So I'm saying that you have them all across the spectrums.

444
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:49,000
Go for it. Go for it. I'm with you.

445
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:51,000
But I'm not going to get in the way.

446
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:53,000
I'm not going to miss the meeting.

447
01:03:53,000 --> 01:03:55,000
But I want to slipy-fired all of us.

448
01:03:55,000 --> 01:04:03,000
So I'm saying I don't believe there was a single black there that was untouched.

449
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:07,000
But you have the extremes of yes and touch.

450
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:09,000
But I'm not going to do anything about it.

451
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:11,000
Either I'm afraid to, or I'm reluctant to.

452
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:13,000
I don't want you to disturb me.

453
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:15,000
I'm doing all right.

454
01:04:15,000 --> 01:04:17,000
Or the others, I say, who?

455
01:04:17,000 --> 01:04:19,000
We going all the way.

456
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:27,000
Now, I do believe there was a pent-up desire for freedom by many blacks.

457
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:33,000
But they didn't like it, but had no way to get out of it.

458
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:47,000
And it was not until Martin Luther King came along that they realized there is a way other than what has been the historic way of something differences.

459
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:55,000
Harking back to the Revolutionary War, the Spanish-American War, we've always settled our differences by wars.

460
01:04:55,000 --> 01:04:57,000
And that was a mindset of people.

461
01:04:57,000 --> 01:05:03,000
We can't beat them because we don't have the guns and whatnot.

462
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:05,000
So we'd be just better learning how to live with it.

463
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:13,000
But then Martin Luther King came along with this new armamentarian, and it was peace and non-violence.

464
01:05:13,000 --> 01:05:17,000
And the fact that it was successful there, these people felt it can't happen here.

465
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:21,000
And would you believe they looked at me to be that Martin Luther King for all many?

466
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:23,000
No, no, no, no, no.

467
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:29,000
So after we finally got the organization together and I was elected president, and the name just emerged.

468
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:33,000
And everybody came and said, well, let's have a whole list of names choose from.

469
01:05:33,000 --> 01:05:37,000
In conversation, somebody said, well, let's call it a movement.

470
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:39,000
And that's how the name happened.

471
01:05:39,000 --> 01:05:40,000
All been a movement.

472
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:48,000
Then I think I said, but none of us have inexperience in this, but I know somebody who does.

473
01:05:49,000 --> 01:05:58,000
And now that marriage, meet Martin Luther King, that job in Montgomery, meet and have Evan Athe.

474
01:05:58,000 --> 01:06:04,000
These are people now that I could get on and call personally, personally.

475
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:06,000
Now there was some reluctant to bring them in.

476
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:07,000
Let me say that.

477
01:06:07,000 --> 01:06:17,000
There was some reluctance because SNCC and NAACP depended on the drama of the hour to build up their coffers,

478
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:20,000
because they brought in more money as there was that.

479
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:32,000
So we decided then we made certain that Martin Luther King and Evan Athe did not come in with the full SNCC organization and take over the ordinary.

480
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:33,000
SCLC.

481
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:35,000
SCLC, right? Where did I say SCLC?

482
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:38,000
SNCC, not come in and take over.

483
01:06:38,000 --> 01:06:43,000
Well, SNCC wanted to make sure that SCLC didn't come and take over.

484
01:06:44,000 --> 01:06:49,000
So then we agreed, okay, he'll come under those conditions.

485
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:57,000
So because my wife and I knew Martin were out well enough that we could call them and ask them to come and let them know what the situation was.

486
01:06:57,000 --> 01:07:07,000
So they came down our invitation and they came to a church rally and this was that...

487
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:09,000
Bewerb Baptist church. Bewerb.

488
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:10,000
I think they were in the church.

489
01:07:10,000 --> 01:07:14,000
Shallow. Shallow. Shallow was the first one. They came to Shallow.

490
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:20,000
How the word got out all those Southwest Georgia, Joe, I will never know.

491
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:24,000
There was no radio, no television, no newspapers and many places.

492
01:07:24,000 --> 01:07:26,000
They didn't have electric lights.

493
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:32,000
But the word spread throughout South Georgia and literally thousands of people came to that mass reading that night.

494
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:38,000
We filled up both churches. Shallow and Mount Zanglet right across the street from each other.

495
01:07:38,000 --> 01:07:42,000
Martin came there, not with an unterraged.

496
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:51,000
He came there with Andy Young, White Walker and Evanathy.

497
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:54,000
I believe that was it, the first trip.

498
01:07:54,000 --> 01:07:59,000
Because his intent was to speak out of rally and go back to Atlanta.

499
01:07:59,000 --> 01:08:05,000
So he spoke at Shallow and he was going to see that you have to go across the street to Mount Zion.

500
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:12,000
And he did. And he was going to see there, of course within his ear, you got to go back to Shallow.

501
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:14,000
I mean, yeah, to Shallow.

502
01:08:14,000 --> 01:08:17,000
And he says, I've done that. And he told me how tired it was.

503
01:08:17,000 --> 01:08:21,000
I said, but these people have been waiting 100 years for you.

504
01:08:21,000 --> 01:08:25,000
And they could not get in these two churches. That's whether in the empty doubt they filled up again.

505
01:08:25,000 --> 01:08:28,000
He spoke four times that one night.

506
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:33,000
And my observation was every time he spoke, he got stronger.

507
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:37,000
And Evanathy was a great warm up man.

508
01:08:37,000 --> 01:08:44,000
You go to these theatrical producers, as always, the warm up act that come before the main act.

509
01:08:44,000 --> 01:08:46,000
Evanathy was great at that.

510
01:08:46,000 --> 01:08:50,000
Then Martin would come on and mesmerize the people.

511
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:53,000
So he did that with no intentions of staying.

512
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:56,000
But when he spoke, huh?

513
01:08:56,000 --> 01:09:01,000
Except when he spoke the last time.

514
01:09:01,000 --> 01:09:09,000
I said to 1000 people here, Martin Luther King is committed to Albany, the Albany Movement.

515
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:13,000
And he's going to come back and be with us throughout.

516
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:21,000
And the young has reported on numerous occasions, I tricked Martin in the coming down there to give a speech.

517
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:24,000
And they committed him to stay.

518
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:27,000
And I say guilty.

519
01:09:27,000 --> 01:09:30,000
I don't deny it was not intended to be trickery.

520
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:33,000
But I had not talked with him about whether he would do it or not.

521
01:09:33,000 --> 01:09:40,000
But I saw. I saw in him a stride toward freedom was being made because I saw how the people.

522
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:42,000
They picked him up and carried him on.

523
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:45,000
Yes, he was kind of tired when he got there.

524
01:09:45,000 --> 01:09:48,000
But the more he spoke, the stronger he got.

525
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:51,000
And he saw these people already.

526
01:09:51,000 --> 01:09:53,000
And Martin could not have done any of this without the people.

527
01:09:53,000 --> 01:09:54,000
We all knew that.

528
01:09:54,000 --> 01:09:57,000
The people had to be ready.

529
01:09:57,000 --> 01:09:58,000
So the next day.

530
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:01,000
And the next day he went back to Atlanta.

531
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:05,000
But then we started having mass meetings every night.

532
01:10:05,000 --> 01:10:08,000
We would have board meetings. We had a board.

533
01:10:08,000 --> 01:10:11,000
Slater King was the vice president.

534
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:16,000
Marion Page was Secretary Treasurer.

535
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:22,000
Goldie Jackson was the secretary.

536
01:10:22,000 --> 01:10:26,000
Bo Jackson was the treasurer.

537
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:28,000
We had a board.

538
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:31,000
And we met every night, if you can imagine.

539
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:35,000
This mass meetings were going some time to ten left for the pocket of late.

540
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:40,000
And then we were going to have mass meetings for a couple of hours after that.

541
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:43,000
And then I would try to practice.

542
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:49,000
I'm also about 25 or 30 pounds over a period of about six, eight months.

543
01:10:49,000 --> 01:10:51,000
Were you also feeling picked up and carried on?

544
01:10:51,000 --> 01:10:53,000
Absolutely.

545
01:10:53,000 --> 01:10:57,000
If you don't get emotional involved, you're not going to take those kind of risks here.

546
01:10:57,000 --> 01:11:04,000
Don't let anybody tell you that I can intellectually sit here and decide I'm going to go into the fire.

547
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:07,000
I'm going to face down the Ku Kerk's clan.

548
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:11,000
You don't do that at an intellectual level.

549
01:11:11,000 --> 01:11:15,000
It's done. It's acted out at the emotional level.

550
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:18,000
Yes. And all of us got emotional involved.

551
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:23,000
And when I can get up in church and say, OK, we go into jail.

552
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:25,000
And 500 people get behind me.

553
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:27,000
You know they didn't sit on think about that.

554
01:11:27,000 --> 01:11:30,000
They didn't go home and figure out who's going to pay the bills while I'm going.

555
01:11:30,000 --> 01:11:33,000
Well, I still have my job. No, no, no.

556
01:11:33,000 --> 01:11:36,000
The people were ready for freedom.

557
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:43,000
They had been enslaved, literally enslaved, emotionally enslaved economically.

558
01:11:43,000 --> 01:11:45,000
They had been enslaved for so many years.

559
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:47,000
They were ready for this change.

560
01:11:47,000 --> 01:11:50,000
The time was right.

561
01:11:50,000 --> 01:11:54,000
Let's talk a little bit about the arrests and going to jail.

562
01:11:54,000 --> 01:11:56,000
Which time?

563
01:11:56,000 --> 01:11:58,000
I'm thinking that first time.

564
01:11:58,000 --> 01:12:00,000
You mean Reverend King and Dr. King and Reverend Edward Apples?

565
01:12:00,000 --> 01:12:03,000
Well, that was not the first time.

566
01:12:03,000 --> 01:12:05,000
The first time.

567
01:12:05,000 --> 01:12:08,000
It was not me again. It was my wife.

568
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:12,000
We had had a rally every night leading up to a Sunday night.

569
01:12:12,000 --> 01:12:17,000
And we announced at the Sunday night, we even had a round of Sunday night on Sunday night.

570
01:12:17,000 --> 01:12:21,000
We said those who are ready to go to jail, we'll meet here Monday morning,

571
01:12:21,000 --> 01:12:25,000
7 o'clock, ready to go to jail.

572
01:12:25,000 --> 01:12:30,000
At breakfast that morning at home and I had three children then.

573
01:12:30,000 --> 01:12:37,000
And I said to my children, before this is over, it is very likely that your father is going to be in jail.

574
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:41,000
I want you to know, I'm going to jail, not for anything. I'm done wrong.

575
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:44,000
I have not heard anybody. I have not stolen. I'm killing anybody.

576
01:12:44,000 --> 01:12:48,000
None of the like thing like that. I'm going to jail for your rights. I'm going to jail.

577
01:12:48,000 --> 01:12:50,000
But we have the right to vote.

578
01:12:50,000 --> 01:12:54,000
Whether they understood it or not, I think they came to appreciate it quite a bit later.

579
01:12:54,000 --> 01:12:58,000
So the next morning, my wife and I, together,

580
01:12:58,000 --> 01:13:01,000
my little king and Abbot, that's when they're there then, that was just us.

581
01:13:01,000 --> 01:13:07,000
We led this group of a couple of hundred people, crazy enough to follow us downtown.

582
01:13:07,000 --> 01:13:14,000
We walked around what we called the town square, right in front of the courthouse, right in front of the jail,

583
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:18,000
all around the block. Nothing happened.

584
01:13:18,000 --> 01:13:22,000
Did it a second time? Nothing happened.

585
01:13:22,000 --> 01:13:25,000
I said to my wife, honey, nothing going to happen today.

586
01:13:25,000 --> 01:13:30,000
I'm going to my office. You take them around one more time and then go back to the church.

587
01:13:30,000 --> 01:13:34,000
So I peeled off with them all, just two blocks away.

588
01:13:34,000 --> 01:13:42,000
That third time around, they were waiting, locked up every one of them, including my wife.

589
01:13:42,000 --> 01:13:46,000
That might be a good time to talk a little bit more about...

590
01:13:46,000 --> 01:13:49,000
Okay. Okay.

591
01:13:49,000 --> 01:13:52,000
We're back on after short break. Dr. Aslan, I want to...

592
01:13:52,000 --> 01:13:55,000
Just mention that, on this occasion, so your wife is in jail.

593
01:13:55,000 --> 01:14:04,000
And tell me about your wife in the ways that matter to this very forceful commitment that she would have

594
01:14:04,000 --> 01:14:09,000
and display in so many ways. And maybe you can broaden from there to reflect a little bit about...

595
01:14:09,000 --> 01:14:15,000
Obviously at that time in those years, there was a pretty sharp split in gender roles.

596
01:14:15,000 --> 01:14:18,000
And that might lead us sometimes to overlook the contributions of one of them.

597
01:14:18,000 --> 01:14:23,000
And I'm interested in your perspectives on her, specifically in women's generally.

598
01:14:23,000 --> 01:14:30,000
First about my wife, who's very, very smart,

599
01:14:30,000 --> 01:14:41,000
she also had a way of getting you to do things that maybe you knew you weren't going to do.

600
01:14:42,000 --> 01:14:50,000
When I say at that every major decision that I made, I attribute it to her.

601
01:14:50,000 --> 01:15:02,000
And the marriage, having the children, going from Des Moines to Flint and Flint to Georgia,

602
01:15:02,000 --> 01:15:08,000
to get involved in the civil rights activity, I'm saying that she...

603
01:15:08,000 --> 01:15:16,000
If she had not been right there with me, I'm certain I would not have done it.

604
01:15:16,000 --> 01:15:21,000
I do believe we had a vision, a shared vision, and how does that happen?

605
01:15:21,000 --> 01:15:31,000
I don't think anybody knows, but few of us are fortunate enough to have a mate that you can share a vision with.

606
01:15:31,000 --> 01:15:38,000
She made a lot of sacrifices to get me through medical school, because I was not one of Meens.

607
01:15:38,000 --> 01:15:42,000
When we got married, we stayed with her mother.

608
01:15:42,000 --> 01:15:49,000
And her mother was not a lady of Meens, she was a lady who was abandoned by her husband and left for children.

609
01:15:49,000 --> 01:15:58,000
And my wife, the oldest, the eldest of the four, became the father, if you would, of her three siblings.

610
01:15:58,000 --> 01:16:09,000
So, she grew up in an environment where she had to assume a lot of adult responsibilities before she was even 17 or 18 years old.

611
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:16,000
So, when I say that when she saw Me, what she saw in Me, I don't know.

612
01:16:16,000 --> 01:16:27,000
But she saw something in Me that I did not see in myself, because there were those occasions when I would in despair, say, there's no way I'm ever going to get out of college.

613
01:16:27,000 --> 01:16:31,000
Get an medical school and become a doctor.

614
01:16:31,000 --> 01:16:38,000
And every time I would appear to be in despair, she would be the one to come along and say, you can do it.

615
01:16:38,000 --> 01:16:41,000
And I'll be with you. You can do it.

616
01:16:41,000 --> 01:16:48,000
So, she literally gave up everything, but peace and comfort and tranquility she had on the home in Atlanta.

617
01:16:49,000 --> 01:16:58,000
When we went out to Des Moines, I went out first, saying something like, well, let me get situated in school.

618
01:16:58,000 --> 01:17:03,000
I cannot afford. I don't have any money. We had $600 who I was named, tuition was $600.

619
01:17:03,000 --> 01:17:06,000
So, she was going to stay with her mother in Atlanta.

620
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:13,000
And I was going to go back to visit at Thanksgiving, maybe Christmas, maybe spring break, maybe summer.

621
01:17:13,000 --> 01:17:22,000
But the lady that I stayed with in a rooming house, Ms. Reeves, I never forget her, Ms. Reeves, Lola Reeves, a wonderful woman also.

622
01:17:22,000 --> 01:17:29,000
She saw me pacing the floor at night and couldn't concentrate, couldn't sit still.

623
01:17:29,000 --> 01:17:37,000
And she said to her neighbors and her family, he's never going to make a two medical school without his family.

624
01:17:38,000 --> 01:17:44,000
So, she converted this one room into three petitions, she said that.

625
01:17:44,000 --> 01:17:49,000
This is your living room, this is your dining room, and this is your kitchen, this is just one big room.

626
01:17:49,000 --> 01:17:51,000
She said, you got to have your family here.

627
01:17:51,000 --> 01:17:54,000
So, she helped me to bring my family up.

628
01:17:54,000 --> 01:18:01,000
And one of my family got there, all of a sudden, my grades went out. She said, I was smiling.

629
01:18:02,000 --> 01:18:04,000
I was able to get two or three jobs.

630
01:18:04,000 --> 01:18:13,000
And it was just the fact that she was there, encouraging me, not ready to abandon me because I had this cock-a-mimmy idea about being a doctor.

631
01:18:13,000 --> 01:18:19,000
And she was just patient, long suffering.

632
01:18:19,000 --> 01:18:28,000
She understood me better than I understood myself and above all, whatever stupid cock-a-mimmy idea came up with, she would support it.

633
01:18:29,000 --> 01:18:35,000
And if it was the wrong idea, she would somehow figure out a way to get me to change it.

634
01:18:35,000 --> 01:18:39,000
So, she was ready to go to Flint with me.

635
01:18:39,000 --> 01:18:46,000
She had been teaching some in Des Moines and she went to Flint and immediately got a job teaching in elementary school.

636
01:18:46,000 --> 01:18:58,000
And so, I married, not just a wife, I married really an experienced mother who had the function as a mother and a father for her siblings.

637
01:18:58,000 --> 01:19:10,000
And she used to say, you act like you're not even listening to me, but you realize after a while, what I'm telling you is the right thing and you do it.

638
01:19:10,000 --> 01:19:16,000
And she said, you stubborn like me and I, you never wanted me to, that a woman is right.

639
01:19:16,000 --> 01:19:24,000
But she says, I always know when I've gotten through to you and made you understand because you would do it.

640
01:19:24,000 --> 01:19:26,000
You wouldn't admit it, but you would do it.

641
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:29,000
So, she was a pillar. She was a pillar.

642
01:19:29,000 --> 01:19:31,000
How did you feel when she was arrested?

643
01:19:31,000 --> 01:19:34,000
I was devastated.

644
01:19:34,000 --> 01:19:41,000
I was devastated because I had no idea where she was, what they were going to do to her for treatment she was getting.

645
01:19:41,000 --> 01:19:43,000
They put her out in Lee County.

646
01:19:43,000 --> 01:19:45,000
I had never been there. I had no idea.

647
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:50,000
It was like a Lee County farm, prison farm.

648
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:56,000
And now I'm with my children, three children, because I've been four by then, the young fourth.

649
01:19:56,000 --> 01:20:00,000
I had it not been for my in-laws. I called them in-laws once removed.

650
01:20:00,000 --> 01:20:10,000
My brother married a lady from Birmingham, Alabama, whose sister married John Chatwell,

651
01:20:10,000 --> 01:20:13,000
who was the director of music at Albany State College.

652
01:20:13,000 --> 01:20:24,000
So when my wife was in jail and I didn't know what to do, I would not stay at home because the clan was having their meeting regularly.

653
01:20:24,000 --> 01:20:29,000
It was the Chatwells, Richard Dean Chatwell and John Chatwell, who says,

654
01:20:29,000 --> 01:20:32,000
we'll take care of your children. Got that?

655
01:20:32,000 --> 01:20:34,000
You go ahead and do what you have to do.

656
01:20:34,000 --> 01:20:41,000
It gave me some comfort to know that my children were well taken care of by John and Richard Dean Chatwell.

657
01:20:41,000 --> 01:20:44,000
So for several days, I didn't see my wife.

658
01:20:44,000 --> 01:20:47,000
I have no communication. I couldn't visit her. I didn't know where.

659
01:20:47,000 --> 01:20:53,000
I was living in a different place every night, but Chatwell was taking care of the family.

660
01:20:54,000 --> 01:20:56,000
That's very interesting.

661
01:20:56,000 --> 01:21:02,000
So I had read where you had written in another place that of course you felt fear,

662
01:21:02,000 --> 01:21:06,000
but not to the extent of paralysis or paranoia.

663
01:21:06,000 --> 01:21:07,000
And that's important.

664
01:21:07,000 --> 01:21:10,000
You can be afraid and not be paralyzed.

665
01:21:10,000 --> 01:21:14,000
But it was necessary for you to take precautions to that level.

666
01:21:14,000 --> 01:21:17,000
That's how pressing the danger was.

667
01:21:17,000 --> 01:21:18,000
It was very interesting.

668
01:21:19,000 --> 01:21:25,000
The Ku Klux Klan had a reputation for murder lynchings,

669
01:21:25,000 --> 01:21:28,000
made him a la teo.

670
01:21:28,000 --> 01:21:30,000
That's the work of the clan doing that kind of stuff.

671
01:21:30,000 --> 01:21:36,000
So I was fully aware of that, but not to the point where I was paralyzed.

672
01:21:36,000 --> 01:21:40,000
In other words, was I going on emotion?

673
01:21:40,000 --> 01:21:43,000
Was I going on nerves?

674
01:21:43,000 --> 01:21:44,000
Yes.

675
01:21:44,000 --> 01:21:49,000
There were those times when I was going strictly on nerves and emotions.

676
01:21:49,000 --> 01:21:52,000
Not intellect would have said, run away from this.

677
01:21:52,000 --> 01:21:54,000
You don't have to take this. You're a doctor.

678
01:21:54,000 --> 01:21:56,000
You got a license in Michigan. You can go back and practice.

679
01:21:56,000 --> 01:21:59,000
No, I couldn't leave. I could not emotionally leave.

680
01:21:59,000 --> 01:22:04,000
Let's talk about the arrests and negotiations with the city.

681
01:22:04,000 --> 01:22:10,000
Well, let's go to when we took the petition.

682
01:22:10,000 --> 01:22:13,000
All the petition said was we took it to the mail.

683
01:22:13,000 --> 01:22:19,000
A point about racial committed to study the problems of segregation and discrimination.

684
01:22:19,000 --> 01:22:20,000
Albany.

685
01:22:20,000 --> 01:22:26,000
I gave it to the mayor myself, Aissa Kelly, who I say was, in my opinion,

686
01:22:26,000 --> 01:22:29,000
had a tendency toward being a liberal.

687
01:22:29,000 --> 01:22:31,000
He took it to the city council.

688
01:22:31,000 --> 01:22:34,000
They were to have their regular city council meeting.

689
01:22:34,000 --> 01:22:36,000
I think I've gone to Monday night.

690
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:39,000
I went to the city council meeting to get the results.

691
01:22:39,000 --> 01:22:44,000
I had just come back over and wake in vacation and we were to send a committee.

692
01:22:44,000 --> 01:22:47,000
Nobody in the committee showed up with me.

693
01:22:47,000 --> 01:22:56,000
I was in the city council chambers and they went throughout the agenda and said nothing about our petition.

694
01:22:56,000 --> 01:23:02,000
I got up in the chambers and said, Mr. Mayor, what about our petition?

695
01:23:02,000 --> 01:23:04,000
I didn't hear anything about it.

696
01:23:04,000 --> 01:23:17,000
He said we met in the executive session before the open meeting and decided there are no common grounds for agreement period.

697
01:23:17,000 --> 01:23:29,000
The newspaper, the next day, Albany Hill reported, black doctor demands the end of segregation immediately and stormed out of the chambers.

698
01:23:29,000 --> 01:23:31,000
City council chambers.

699
01:23:31,000 --> 01:23:34,000
He published me in the newspaper next day.

700
01:23:34,000 --> 01:23:35,000
And your address?

701
01:23:35,000 --> 01:23:36,000
My address.

702
01:23:36,000 --> 01:23:40,000
I started getting phone calls with threatening calls.

703
01:23:40,000 --> 01:23:44,000
You can just imagine the kind of calls I was getting.

704
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:47,000
Did you know James Gray, the publisher of it?

705
01:23:47,000 --> 01:23:57,000
From a distance I knew that he was a rabbet segregationist who ironically made a complete turnaround after I left.

706
01:23:57,000 --> 01:24:04,000
And actually he became a business partner for a black doctor who came to town to go over my practice.

707
01:24:04,000 --> 01:24:15,000
So it's amazing how once you take that yoke of segregation and discrimination over some white people, they become real people.

708
01:24:15,000 --> 01:24:19,000
And they put aside their racist attitudes.

709
01:24:19,000 --> 01:24:21,000
And Gray was one of those.

710
01:24:21,000 --> 01:24:25,000
Gray was more of a business person than he was a racist.

711
01:24:25,000 --> 01:24:36,000
And when he had an opportunity to capitalize on this side, he gave up his, he gave him a grand membership because he was an opportunity to be a business man.

712
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:37,000
Dr. Gordon.

713
01:24:37,000 --> 01:24:42,000
Dr. Gordon became a business partner of Gray.

714
01:24:42,000 --> 01:24:45,000
Carl Gordon.

715
01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:50,000
They had a radio station together, they did some things and news paper together.

716
01:24:50,000 --> 01:24:54,000
Other business Carl Gordon is dead now, but they became business partners.

717
01:24:54,000 --> 01:25:10,000
How about the, let's talk about the kind of famous and much discussed moment when Dr. King takes bail on the presumption that the city will come through with some concessions and an honor for coming.

718
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:21,000
But on the, on that fateful day that you mentioned when King and I locked arms, abandoned my wife or directly behind us.

719
01:25:21,000 --> 01:25:24,000
And this was the march where we had over 1000 people.

720
01:25:24,000 --> 01:25:32,000
And we were marching down through Harlem, the main street from downtown, from, from, from the Harlem downtown.

721
01:25:32,000 --> 01:25:40,000
They had called in the international guard, the national guard, the line in the streets of Albany with ready arm.

722
01:25:40,000 --> 01:25:42,000
They had their guns.

723
01:25:42,000 --> 01:25:46,000
You got to presume they were loaded, they were there.

724
01:25:46,000 --> 01:25:55,000
One of the guardsmen stepped in front of me, marching, I would together, and say, you will stop this march now and raise up his gun.

725
01:25:56,000 --> 01:26:03,000
I said to him, if you hit anybody in this line, hit me first, hit me first.

726
01:26:03,000 --> 01:26:09,000
He took the gun down and stepped aside and we marched on down.

727
01:26:09,000 --> 01:26:12,000
All of us got arrested.

728
01:26:12,000 --> 01:26:17,000
Martin, Ralph and I were put in the same jail cell.

729
01:26:17,000 --> 01:26:21,000
It is coincidental that Martin was scheduled to go and meet the press.

730
01:26:21,000 --> 01:26:28,000
I said, my wife out to these brick of the year, but he was scheduled to go and meet the press.

731
01:26:28,000 --> 01:26:35,000
And the, who was the moderator for me to press?

732
01:26:35,000 --> 01:26:37,000
Lawrence Bevac was one who kept calling.

733
01:26:37,000 --> 01:26:49,000
Lawrence Bevac, he kept calling the jail, calling the chief of police, Larry Pritchett, saying that Martin Luther King has got to come out of jail because he's to be on program tomorrow morning.

734
01:26:49,000 --> 01:26:55,000
And Martin would say, I am not coming out of jail until these people read us sit down and talk.

735
01:26:55,000 --> 01:26:58,000
And that was what it was all about. He wouldn't come out.

736
01:26:58,000 --> 01:27:02,000
But then Martin said, being on meet the press is too important.

737
01:27:02,000 --> 01:27:04,000
We've got to get the message out.

738
01:27:04,000 --> 01:27:07,000
It's too important of a venue to get the message out.

739
01:27:07,000 --> 01:27:11,000
So one of us has to go on that program.

740
01:27:11,000 --> 01:27:14,000
I didn't have that kind of experience.

741
01:27:14,000 --> 01:27:22,000
We drew straws. We've seen the jail sale and drew straws. I drew the short straw. And Martin says, you're going to meet the press.

742
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:23,000
You're going to meet the press.

743
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:25,000
Just like that.

744
01:27:25,000 --> 01:27:28,000
We left about that some years later. Just like that.

745
01:27:28,000 --> 01:27:32,000
We drew straws to see who would come out of jail to go and meet the press.

746
01:27:32,000 --> 01:27:37,000
He said, when you had to get a hosepawn and get on an airplane and fly to the outside.

747
01:27:37,000 --> 01:27:40,000
And you drew the short straw.

748
01:27:41,000 --> 01:27:44,000
And Clarence Jones, who's a lawyer for MLT,

749
01:27:44,000 --> 01:27:46,000
was the one who also met me in New York.

750
01:27:46,000 --> 01:27:49,000
And that night I was up most of that being briefed.

751
01:27:49,000 --> 01:27:53,000
The transcript of Meet the Press is in that book you just got.

752
01:27:57,000 --> 01:28:07,000
What was your reaction as events would unfold and you'd have this reversal with the city?

753
01:28:07,000 --> 01:28:12,000
On what you thought was something forthcoming in terms of some concessions.

754
01:28:12,000 --> 01:28:15,000
When we, we'll move our rest of it again.

755
01:28:15,000 --> 01:28:18,000
And this time in America's.

756
01:28:18,000 --> 01:28:23,000
And they took us out of jail Monday morning and took us into court.

757
01:28:23,000 --> 01:28:26,000
There were three blikes.

758
01:28:26,000 --> 01:28:31,000
I believe Chapman, Cochran.

759
01:28:31,000 --> 01:28:35,000
And a guy who was the local manager of Pilgrim Insurance Company.

760
01:28:36,000 --> 01:28:41,000
And I might think of his name, but three blikes and three whites.

761
01:28:41,000 --> 01:28:44,000
The whites were what?

762
01:28:44,000 --> 01:28:47,000
A member of City Council.

763
01:28:47,000 --> 01:28:50,000
And two others who I do not know who they were.

764
01:28:50,000 --> 01:28:58,000
But anyway, these six people met behind closed doors.

765
01:28:58,000 --> 01:29:04,000
And that was the verbal agreement made that we will meet your demands for the by-risk account.

766
01:29:05,000 --> 01:29:08,000
A point met a by-risk committee.

767
01:29:08,000 --> 01:29:14,000
And we will study the issues of segregation and discrimination in the city facilities.

768
01:29:14,000 --> 01:29:16,000
Verbal.

769
01:29:16,000 --> 01:29:25,000
They came out and Hallowell say, will there be a joint press conference if not a written document?

770
01:29:25,000 --> 01:29:27,000
There was no written document.

771
01:29:27,000 --> 01:29:29,000
Hallowell, of course, being the African-American term.

772
01:29:29,000 --> 01:29:35,000
Don Hallowell, Martin, Martin Luther King said, we need a written document,

773
01:29:35,000 --> 01:29:38,000
a written statement for the press.

774
01:29:38,000 --> 01:29:43,000
At the very least, a press conference ensay it to the press.

775
01:29:43,000 --> 01:29:46,000
They did not do either one.

776
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:51,000
Hallowell was a fine lawyer.

777
01:29:51,000 --> 01:29:58,000
But he was more willing to accept them at their word that they would do that.

778
01:29:59,000 --> 01:30:03,000
That he did not insist on putting it right in all having the press conference.

779
01:30:03,000 --> 01:30:08,000
Martin and I were sitting next together in the courtroom and he says, I don't like this.

780
01:30:08,000 --> 01:30:11,000
I'm sorry, I don't really like this.

781
01:30:11,000 --> 01:30:13,000
But everybody was out of jail.

782
01:30:13,000 --> 01:30:15,000
They signed what they called straw bonds.

783
01:30:15,000 --> 01:30:18,000
But none of them were ever called back.

784
01:30:18,000 --> 01:30:21,000
We were called back.

785
01:30:21,000 --> 01:30:24,000
Abinathy King and I were called back for trial.

786
01:30:25,000 --> 01:30:29,000
And of course, it was like a kangaroo court because when you go into the courtroom,

787
01:30:29,000 --> 01:30:33,000
they judge already had the decision already written out.

788
01:30:33,000 --> 01:30:37,000
And with a prosecutor attorney and the defense attorney's, but finished making that presentation,

789
01:30:37,000 --> 01:30:41,000
he said, oh, here's my decision.

790
01:30:41,000 --> 01:30:47,000
But they reneged on everything they said in that conference.

791
01:30:47,000 --> 01:30:53,000
Now, it was reported that Martin Luther King failed in Albany because he did not do that.

792
01:30:53,000 --> 01:30:56,000
Because he did not get anything.

793
01:30:56,000 --> 01:31:02,000
However, one by one, they closed every public facility.

794
01:31:02,000 --> 01:31:11,000
Library, parks, swimming pool, bus, lunch, count us, everything was closed.

795
01:31:11,000 --> 01:31:14,000
What did we get out of Albany?

796
01:31:14,000 --> 01:31:15,000
Yes.

797
01:31:15,000 --> 01:31:16,000
Go ahead.

798
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:17,000
All right, go ahead.

799
01:31:17,000 --> 01:31:18,000
All right.

800
01:31:18,000 --> 01:31:19,000
Sure.

801
01:31:20,000 --> 01:31:26,000
There's also the, you know, in the summer, 62.

802
01:31:26,000 --> 01:31:30,000
When he comes back from that sentencing hall, he came in the CLC.

803
01:31:30,000 --> 01:31:37,000
They want to see if they can't reintegrate the movement and push forward.

804
01:31:37,000 --> 01:31:40,000
He brings staff to Albany.

805
01:31:40,000 --> 01:31:44,000
He is arrested again.

806
01:31:44,000 --> 01:31:52,000
And this time, there's actually, but in front of that, there's the hostel, frankly,

807
01:31:52,000 --> 01:31:56,000
the hostel local federal judge.

808
01:31:56,000 --> 01:31:57,000
J. Robert Elliott.

809
01:31:57,000 --> 01:31:58,000
Exactly.

810
01:31:58,000 --> 01:31:59,000
Robert Elliott.

811
01:31:59,000 --> 01:32:00,000
I know.

812
01:32:00,000 --> 01:32:02,000
He issues an injunction, I mean, further protest.

813
01:32:02,000 --> 01:32:09,000
And there's the question in July, four days, just you should have Dr. King ignore or appear to that injunction.

814
01:32:09,000 --> 01:32:17,800
We appealed and went to Atlanta before Judge Tuffle, Albert Tuffle.

815
01:32:17,800 --> 01:32:24,720
And we were represented there, not just by Ternikin and Hollywood, but that's where Constance

816
01:32:24,720 --> 01:32:27,480
Motley came.

817
01:32:27,480 --> 01:32:28,480
Constance Motley.

818
01:32:28,480 --> 01:32:32,600
And of course, the state was represented by the best that the state had to offer because

819
01:32:32,600 --> 01:32:37,080
they brought lawyers in from Emory, from the first of Georgia.

820
01:32:37,160 --> 01:32:42,800
And they cited case after case after case where we were breaking the laws and Constance

821
01:32:42,800 --> 01:32:49,520
Motley without benefit of a single note stood up there and refuted every one of the cases

822
01:32:49,520 --> 01:32:51,680
that cited and would say.

823
01:32:51,680 --> 01:32:57,200
And if Ternikin from the University of Georgia had looked at how this was appealed and

824
01:32:57,200 --> 01:32:59,400
next year it was reversed.

825
01:32:59,400 --> 01:33:01,240
I mean she was amazing.

826
01:33:01,240 --> 01:33:05,200
She just, and Albert Tuffle could do nothing but sit there in wonder.

827
01:33:05,200 --> 01:33:09,560
She had never seen a black female lawyer.

828
01:33:09,560 --> 01:33:10,560
That's smart.

829
01:33:10,560 --> 01:33:11,560
And of course.

830
01:33:11,560 --> 01:33:22,800
Karatiska King would later write that she thought that the quote was, that the failure

831
01:33:22,800 --> 01:33:27,280
to ignore the injunction of the head was quote, that the factor that broke the backbone

832
01:33:27,280 --> 01:33:32,000
of the movement in that moment, in that possible moment.

833
01:33:32,000 --> 01:33:33,000
Was that your idea?

834
01:33:33,000 --> 01:33:40,840
The thing that broke the back of it was the reneging on the part of the city for what

835
01:33:40,840 --> 01:33:42,240
was agreed on.

836
01:33:42,240 --> 01:33:47,120
In other words, we've all elated because we had come to the agreement, we got what we

837
01:33:47,120 --> 01:33:50,760
asked for.

838
01:33:50,760 --> 01:33:53,920
But then one by one, they closed all the facilities.

839
01:33:53,920 --> 01:33:56,200
So yeah, you've got it.

840
01:33:56,200 --> 01:33:59,040
But what did it mean?

841
01:33:59,040 --> 01:34:05,560
It's like I won a 757 airplane and don't know how to fly a kite.

842
01:34:05,560 --> 01:34:10,560
So it was a failure in that we did not get anything tangible out of it.

843
01:34:10,560 --> 01:34:17,960
But what we got out of it though was the change in the attitudes and the perceptions.

844
01:34:17,960 --> 01:34:23,840
White people had come to believe and I really think they believed it sincerely.

845
01:34:23,840 --> 01:34:28,080
Black folks like it this way.

846
01:34:28,080 --> 01:34:34,400
They are satisfying at being servants.

847
01:34:34,400 --> 01:34:38,320
So the attitudes change because the perception change.

848
01:34:38,320 --> 01:34:39,640
No, they don't like this.

849
01:34:39,640 --> 01:34:40,880
And look what they did.

850
01:34:40,880 --> 01:34:43,640
They rose up against us.

851
01:34:43,640 --> 01:34:47,680
So maybe we have to look at them differently.

852
01:34:47,680 --> 01:34:56,440
Black folks of course found courage in this new way to change the system and do it non-violently.

853
01:34:56,440 --> 01:34:59,360
And so now they have made a determination.

854
01:34:59,360 --> 01:35:02,400
You know we can change this so we're not going to take it anymore.

855
01:35:02,400 --> 01:35:03,400
That was enough.

856
01:35:03,400 --> 01:35:08,760
When the attitudes were changed and the perceptions were changed, that was the end of segregation

857
01:35:08,760 --> 01:35:12,440
and discrimination as it was known prior to that time.

858
01:35:12,440 --> 01:35:15,200
No, I'm very much agree.

859
01:35:15,200 --> 01:35:22,480
I think that all of the people that go back up, we're back out of the same.

860
01:35:22,480 --> 01:35:29,280
I think Albany was part of a long unfolding process that involved struggling many places

861
01:35:29,280 --> 01:35:33,960
and it was instrumental in the local ways you mentioned.

862
01:35:33,960 --> 01:35:38,920
In what it showed by way of inspiration, what it showed by way of model and tactics and

863
01:35:38,920 --> 01:35:45,360
strategy and mass action, but there's no question.

864
01:35:45,360 --> 01:35:48,800
How are you feeling by late summer of 62?

865
01:35:49,800 --> 01:35:52,400
It's a lot of stress and strain.

866
01:35:52,400 --> 01:35:55,840
I was literally exhausted.

867
01:35:55,840 --> 01:36:02,360
At one point I was exhausted to the point where my wife again, she said you had to go away

868
01:36:02,360 --> 01:36:05,080
and get some rest.

869
01:36:05,080 --> 01:36:10,360
I was emotional and high, but physically I was deteriorating.

870
01:36:10,360 --> 01:36:13,520
So she took me from Albany, took me over to Tuskegee.

871
01:36:13,520 --> 01:36:14,520
I was a veteran.

872
01:36:14,520 --> 01:36:18,320
Took me to the Veterans House Bill to make sure that I was physically alright.

873
01:36:18,320 --> 01:36:22,440
I had checked around a couple of days and then she took me to her grandfather's home in

874
01:36:22,440 --> 01:36:23,440
Silicaga.

875
01:36:23,440 --> 01:36:31,920
He was a minister and I needed him for that spiritual revitalization.

876
01:36:31,920 --> 01:36:38,280
So between those two in a week, I was ready to go back into battle, but I needed that.

877
01:36:38,280 --> 01:36:47,520
I needed the assurance that physically I'm alright, but also needed that emotional strength.

878
01:36:47,520 --> 01:36:50,280
Now I am not a religious fanatic.

879
01:36:50,280 --> 01:36:51,280
Let me say that.

880
01:36:51,280 --> 01:37:00,560
I'm not a religious fanatic, but I do believe that if they divine plan, I do feel as though

881
01:37:00,560 --> 01:37:07,640
it was meant to be that I would wind up in Albany, Georgia, leading a civil movement.

882
01:37:07,640 --> 01:37:12,800
Otherwise how did I marry this lady that put me with Martin Luther King?

883
01:37:12,800 --> 01:37:16,640
I don't wind up going to Montgomery Falls places and meet Abanatha.

884
01:37:16,640 --> 01:37:22,240
I mean, these things, in my opinion, just don't happen.

885
01:37:22,240 --> 01:37:29,200
Now whether you believe in God or Maui or Allah or whoever, I do believe that everyone

886
01:37:29,200 --> 01:37:32,400
has a purpose and everyone has a purpose in life.

887
01:37:32,400 --> 01:37:38,640
And as much as you try to ignore it, you can't.

888
01:37:38,640 --> 01:37:45,560
Tell me about, you mentioned that very interesting fact that afterwards you would develop something

889
01:37:45,560 --> 01:37:50,840
in relationship with good terms with Lord Krishna.

890
01:37:50,840 --> 01:37:56,720
A few years after the man, I went back down to all of the two or three years later when

891
01:37:56,720 --> 01:37:58,720
things were beginning to settle down now.

892
01:37:58,720 --> 01:38:02,600
No more demonstrations, no more arrests, no court hearings.

893
01:38:02,600 --> 01:38:10,320
I was down there for something and I made what a policeman said was an illegal term.

894
01:38:10,320 --> 01:38:12,760
And he said, I'm going to give you a ticket for what?

895
01:38:12,760 --> 01:38:14,400
He said, you made illegal money.

896
01:38:14,400 --> 01:38:15,400
So no, I didn't.

897
01:38:15,400 --> 01:38:16,400
You give me the argument.

898
01:38:16,400 --> 01:38:17,400
Yeah, I didn't do that.

899
01:38:17,400 --> 01:38:18,400
You go in the jail.

900
01:38:18,400 --> 01:38:20,520
All right, take me to jail.

901
01:38:20,520 --> 01:38:24,000
So he took me to jail and who was in jail?

902
01:38:24,000 --> 01:38:25,000
She printed.

903
01:38:25,000 --> 01:38:28,400
I was being booked and she printed, heard me from his office.

904
01:38:28,400 --> 01:38:30,640
He said, is that Doc Anderson out there?

905
01:38:30,640 --> 01:38:31,640
Yeah.

906
01:38:31,920 --> 01:38:33,720
Come into my office.

907
01:38:33,720 --> 01:38:35,480
What's he, what you resting for?

908
01:38:35,480 --> 01:38:36,480
He made illegal terms.

909
01:38:36,480 --> 01:38:37,880
He said, give me that ticket.

910
01:38:37,880 --> 01:38:42,400
He said, you'll never rest him in this town for illegal turning.

911
01:38:42,400 --> 01:38:45,400
He'll have to have a demonstration down here.

912
01:38:45,400 --> 01:38:48,800
But then we were on friendly terms.

913
01:38:48,800 --> 01:38:52,920
The next time we got together was when eyes on the priors being filmed in Atlanta,

914
01:38:52,920 --> 01:38:56,520
several years later, he heard that I was coming.

915
01:38:56,520 --> 01:39:00,840
I knew he was coming because the producers had contacted all of us who had been

916
01:39:00,840 --> 01:39:03,760
active in the Albina movement.

917
01:39:03,760 --> 01:39:07,560
He got there, he had a me and he ordered to find a way I was staying and he literally

918
01:39:07,560 --> 01:39:09,800
met me at the hotel.

919
01:39:09,800 --> 01:39:11,800
Can we have dinner together?

920
01:39:11,800 --> 01:39:17,480
My wife and his wife, the four of us, when I had dinner together and we relived those days

921
01:39:17,480 --> 01:39:19,000
in Albini.

922
01:39:19,000 --> 01:39:24,760
Thereafter, he visited me in Detroit because he would go up to Michigan State every once

923
01:39:24,760 --> 01:39:29,720
and a while for some police stuff and I would go down to North Carolina, high point, North

924
01:39:29,720 --> 01:39:30,920
Carolina.

925
01:39:30,920 --> 01:39:33,720
We exchanged cards regularly.

926
01:39:33,720 --> 01:39:36,720
We became good friends up until his death.

927
01:39:36,720 --> 01:39:43,120
So the civil right movement emancipated some white folks and he's an example of how,

928
01:39:43,120 --> 01:39:49,080
because he was basically a decent man as was Kelly, but trapped.

929
01:39:50,080 --> 01:39:51,280
So you think it's interesting.

930
01:39:51,280 --> 01:39:57,960
So looking at that span of years after through the 70s and 80s, you think that you think that

931
01:39:57,960 --> 01:40:01,360
Laurie Pritchett could become a different person?

932
01:40:01,360 --> 01:40:04,680
Or I should say his views about race had been fundamentally changed.

933
01:40:04,680 --> 01:40:07,320
Oh, absolutely, but one of them waited a minute.

934
01:40:07,320 --> 01:40:11,240
I said, I think basically, fundamentally, he was the decent man.

935
01:40:11,240 --> 01:40:12,800
He was not a racist.

936
01:40:12,800 --> 01:40:14,560
That was not him.

937
01:40:15,560 --> 01:40:20,880
He had been placed in a position where he had to do what the City Council said.

938
01:40:20,880 --> 01:40:25,760
If he had been free to do what he wanted to do, he bucked the City Council when he refused

939
01:40:25,760 --> 01:40:33,160
to let his policeman perpetrate any violence against the people because ball-conner set the

940
01:40:33,160 --> 01:40:36,640
example that this is the last thing you want to do, beat all these people up with all

941
01:40:36,640 --> 01:40:38,640
the cameras of the world.

942
01:40:38,640 --> 01:40:42,720
Because in Albini, literally, reporters of all of the world came to Albini and he said,

943
01:40:42,720 --> 01:40:46,960
that's the last thing I want is this to go all over the world that we policemen beat

944
01:40:46,960 --> 01:40:49,640
up people like they'd do in South Africa.

945
01:40:49,640 --> 01:40:51,680
So he didn't work that.

946
01:40:51,680 --> 01:40:56,280
So all he needed was the opportunity to get out of that.

947
01:40:56,280 --> 01:40:56,960
And if A.C.

948
01:40:56,960 --> 01:41:00,400
Kelly had lived, I believe he would have been the same way.

949
01:41:00,400 --> 01:41:03,400
I was in Albini a month or a go.

950
01:41:03,400 --> 01:41:10,520
Well, you were there for one of the events, but I was down there for SNCC also, their anniversary.

951
01:41:10,520 --> 01:41:15,440
I went down there with a lady by the name of Rhea Hyle.

952
01:41:15,440 --> 01:41:18,440
Rhea Hyle.

953
01:41:18,440 --> 01:41:23,440
She's happy to be chairman of the board of one of the Detroit Medical Center hospitals.

954
01:41:23,440 --> 01:41:29,080
Needless to say, she's white.

955
01:41:29,080 --> 01:41:33,760
We went down there to Albini together.

956
01:41:33,760 --> 01:41:36,520
We went to everything together.

957
01:41:36,520 --> 01:41:39,760
There was barely a second look.

958
01:41:39,760 --> 01:41:45,600
Albini has been desegregated to the point where it's as though it always has been this

959
01:41:45,600 --> 01:41:48,120
way.

960
01:41:48,120 --> 01:41:52,040
The federal court building is named after CB King.

961
01:41:52,040 --> 01:41:57,000
The mayor, really Adams, is black.

962
01:41:57,000 --> 01:42:02,880
Sheriff, black, former chief of police, black.

963
01:42:02,880 --> 01:42:05,880
We went out to true through restaurants while we were down there and I had to call that

964
01:42:05,880 --> 01:42:06,880
attention.

965
01:42:06,880 --> 01:42:11,680
Honey, you look around here and every table where you see a group, every one to black, I

966
01:42:11,680 --> 01:42:14,600
say, this would never have been 50 years ago.

967
01:42:14,600 --> 01:42:17,880
So ask me, was it worth it?

968
01:42:17,880 --> 01:42:21,120
Was it worth it?

969
01:42:21,120 --> 01:42:29,460
Then the crowning experience of this trip was to go back to America's Georgia, the

970
01:42:29,460 --> 01:42:30,460
Wingo Hotel.

971
01:42:30,460 --> 01:42:37,340
If you ever get a chance to go to Wingo Hotel, it was an old aristocratic hotel where Jimic

972
01:42:37,340 --> 01:42:41,540
Carter stayed, where Al Capone stayed.

973
01:42:41,540 --> 01:42:43,700
I was there at Bellhop.

974
01:42:43,700 --> 01:42:49,340
I did some other things that might have been somewhat illegal, but whatever the customer

975
01:42:49,340 --> 01:42:51,060
wanted, I got it as a Bellhop.

976
01:42:51,060 --> 01:42:52,540
I was 13 years old.

977
01:42:53,540 --> 01:42:55,860
That was a pin-out suite there.

978
01:42:55,860 --> 01:43:02,020
I could never have imagined staying in that pin-out suite as a guest.

979
01:43:02,020 --> 01:43:11,380
I went there with this lady of German descent and stayed in the pin-out suite.

980
01:43:11,380 --> 01:43:17,340
Was it worth it that I could do that freely now?

981
01:43:17,340 --> 01:43:18,340
It was worth it.

982
01:43:19,340 --> 01:43:26,340
Did your children, how did your children talk to you over the years about their recollection

983
01:43:26,340 --> 01:43:29,340
with that experience?

984
01:43:29,340 --> 01:43:34,940
Two of the three of them were old enough to realize what was going on and they wanted

985
01:43:34,940 --> 01:43:39,140
to get in it because they were high school kids.

986
01:43:39,140 --> 01:43:45,580
If you read the transcript from Meet the Press, I was chastised by Kielpatrick.

987
01:43:45,580 --> 01:43:46,580
You get children out there.

988
01:43:46,580 --> 01:43:52,060
It's their citizens also.

989
01:43:52,060 --> 01:43:57,660
High school kids were in the marches going to jail and really for them it was fun.

990
01:43:57,660 --> 01:43:58,660
It was.

991
01:43:58,660 --> 01:44:04,580
They were laughing and talking and singing all the time and the sheriff would come in and

992
01:44:04,580 --> 01:44:06,580
